95	0.2	7	NewsDATA	How Trump’s tariffs are shaking up tech — and giving Europe an edge	Bojan Stojkovski is a freelance journalist who has been covering foreign policy and EU affairs for more than a decade. Based in Skopje, North Macedonia, he reports on technology, science, and environmental issues, as well as human rights and post-war societies in the western Balkan countries. His work has been featured in global media outlets such as Foreign Policy, Interesting Engineering, ZDNET, the Wall Street Journal, and Haaretz among others. c천지일보.What happens when global powers clash over trade? Stock markets tumble. Executives panic. The news cycles spin. But in the shadow of that chaos, something else takes shape — something quieter but far more transformative: an opportunity for innovation.US President Donald Trump’s sweeping new tariff plan — including a flat 10% levy announced this April — is rattling confidence across global markets. Wall Street is nervous, Beijing is retaliating and Brussels is recalculating. And yet, while multinationals scramble, some of the most exciting developments are happening far from the boardrooms — in startup hubs from Slovenia to Poland.This isn’t just a trade war, it’s a seismic shift. And like any shift, it creates cracks — cracks that can be filled by regional innovation.History has shown us this pattern before. Large corporations, built for scale not speed, stall when the status quo breaks. Meanwhile, startups — lean, local, and adaptive — move fast. We saw it during the 2008 crisis, again during the pandemic, and we’re seeing it now. Today’s global disorder is forcing a rethink. For Europe’s tech entrepreneurs, that could be very good news.Three reasons Europe’s startups are better positioned right nowFor years, U.S. firms have dominated the export of digital services. But as tariffs squeeze margins and inject uncertainty, their edge is slipping. Already, European companies are seeing more inbound interest — from Asia, from Latin America, and even from the Global South — looking for partners not caught in Washington’s crossfire.The European market is also gaining weight. For once, startups can build for a growing, tech-hungry region without relying on Silicon Valley validation. There’s potential here not just to compete — but to lead.The U.S. has long drawn top talent from across the world, especially in STEM. But Trump’s return to the White House has sparked fresh fears: visa uncertainty, grant withdrawals, and what many researchers describe as a hostile policy environment.Nature’s recent poll found that 75% of leading scientists are actively considering leaving the U.S., and Europe is now ready to catch them.Twelve EU countries are calling for emergency research incentives. The European Research Council is doubling its relocation grants. And governments from Portugal to Poland are stepping up efforts to attract researchers and founders back to the continent. This isn’t just about talent retention, it’s about a brain gain — and Europe’s second chance to build globally competitive deep tech ecosystems.The cargo ships, Emilia, right, and Proficiency, left, pass into the Port of Antwerp, near Doel, Belgium, Thursday, June 20, 2024. (AP Photo/Virginia Mayo, 뉴시스)Eastern and Southeastern Europe finally gaining visibilityMassive funding channels like Horizon Europe are already distributing billions across the continent. But what’s more important for the region is this: Eastern and Southeastern Europe are finally on the radar — not just as recipients of support, but as strategic players in shaping Europe’s future. Once viewed as peripheral, these regions are now emerging as critical contributors to the continent’s digital, scientific, and technological sovereignty.Much like the Ukraine war triggered a renewed push for energy independence, Trump’s tariffs and escalating trade tensions are acting as a wake-up call for digital resilience. Europe is recognizing the risks of overreliance on foreign — particularly U.S. — tech monopolies for essentials like cloud infrastructure, artificial intelligence, and semiconductor production. A growing consensus in Brussels is clear: the future must be built at home. That creates a rare window of opportunity for founders across the region to step into the spotlight.What this new phase of trade and tech rivalry is revealing is that global fragmentation isn’t just a talking point anymore — it’s becoming a daily reality. And in that reality, startups that design with the European market in mind from day one will have a clear edge. It’s not just about understanding the regulatory environment; it’s about riding the political momentum. Researchers are relocating from the U.S., skilled professionals from the region are returning home, and digital sovereignty is climbing up the EU’s policy agenda. All of this creates a unique moment for building high-impact teams with global credentials — right here.As U.S. tech companies face increasing friction operating abroad, gaps will start to show — in edtech, fintech, AI, biotech, and beyond. That’s where agile, locally grounded startups can move fast and fill the void.Let’s be clear: protectionism isn’t the answer, and in many cases it reflects a short-sighted reaction to global complexity. But if you're building a startup in Europe right now, you’re not stuck on the sidelines — you’re in a position to shape the next chapter of the global economy.From cancer research in Romania to edtech in Bulgaria, from supply chain innovation in North Macedonia to quantum computing in Germany — the ground is shifting. Founders just need to recognize it, and plant their feet firmly in it.	ONLY AVAILABLE IN PAID PLANS	https://www.newscj.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=3265674	https://www.newscj.com/news/photo/202505/3265674_3328904_2140.jpg	2025-05-04 22:00:00
